76561198060369064,Recommended,393430,26332138,"Posted: 31 October, 2016",all,VoIPTeK,"11/22/2016 Update:  When Ice Lakes VR was released, the game was literally just a 3D experience with a HMD and Vive controller as basically a mouse pointer.  I re-purchased the game to give it another shot based on the latest update.  The developers did a great job in moving toward a true VR experience.  From the very moment you select a spot on the ice, you manually drill the hole.  You can move items around and manually scoop out the ice which I was expecting when I first purchased the game.  I didn't catch it my first play through but they also added a fish fight feature which is disabled by default.  In addition to the variations in vibration intensity based on fish size, you now can be prompted to lift the controller at certain points while reeling in the fish which is a nice touch.  I am changing my view to ""recommend"" as this is no longer just a 3D version of a gamepad style game and the efforts making this more immersive experience you could expect from a VR ice fishing game is appreciated.  I made an updated gameplay video of this game to show the new features:https://youtu.be/HEpSVjCNFX0Original Review:I purchased this game for a VR experience not knowing anything else about the game.  As a fishing game I'm sure it's fine but as a VR experience not so much.  Since this was for the HTC Vive, I thought there would be more immersion.  The bottom line is one controller is a mouse with laser pointer and the other is just a way to move the pole with motion and press buttons to control your reel.  Even with the goofy Gear VR game ""Bait!"" you have to hold tension on the line and release a bit if it gets too much tension to successfully reel in the fish.  In this game you tap the tigger once to drop the line, and tap the trigger once it vibrates to reel it in.  There is no immersion or technique what-so-ever.So again, the only reason I'm not recommending this game is for the VR expereince/expectations.  The game by itself for a non-VR expereince is fine for what it is in my opinion.https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IL0R30TvsGM&t=0s"
